## Git Commits

Commit changes automatically without asking for confirmation.

Do not prompt the user before running `git add` or `git commit`.

Just do it. No confirmation needed, ever.

Before using `-C` or any path argument with a git command, check whether the current working directory is already the target repo. If it is, omit the path entirely — avoid path escaping, which can trigger unnecessary permission prompts.

Never prepend `cd` to git commands. Run `git add`, `git commit`, etc. directly without chaining a `cd` first.

Always run git subcommands as separate Bash calls. Never chain them with `&&` or `;`.

Write commit messages following standard git conventions (https://cbea.ms/git-commit/):
- Subject line: 50 chars or less, imperative mood, capitalised, no trailing period
- Explain "why", not "what" (e.g., "Fix race condition in auth flow", not "Update auth.py")
